reviews.name: Kay Period
reviews.text:
The good: the beans are pretty great, I've pulled some of the best espresso of my life using their Elevate blend. Their mail order beans were a staple for me during the pandemic.

The meh: In terms of speciality coffee I'd rate the quality of drinks as average. Miles ahead of Starbucks for sure but on par with other specialty chains like Birch and Stumptown. Probably a matter of taste but I prefer the iced coffee and espresso drinks from Blue Bottle.

The bad: I've visited often on weekdays and always had super nice baristas. In the past I've asked where's the bathroom and they always point me downstairs. I visited this Saturday and made my way toward the bathroom when the barista nastily chided me "where do you think you're going???" as if I've strolled through the TSA after setting off the metal detectors. I stuttered out "uh the bathroom" and then added that my friend was in line to order in case her problem was she thought I wasn't a customer. She took a pause and said "bathroom is closed!" I took my friend out of the line and headed somewhere else. Maybe that bathroom downstairs was always meant for employees only, but I had no idea based on the way other employees had directed me there. Either way, any establishment serving coffee needs to offer a place to return their product if you know what I mean. But bottom line, she was so unnecessarily rude it kinda ruined my day, or at least had me fuming for the next few hours, and it makes me hesitate to visit again. It was a relief when I arrived at 11th st Cafe which had a public bathroom and a very sweet barista who made me feel at home and a lovely chill atmosphere to boot.
reviews.responseFromOwnerText:
Hey Kay,

Thank you for taking the time out to let us know about your experience at our West Village cafe. While I can't know exactly what happened, I do apologize for the way that you were spoken to upon your visit. I am aware that we did have some water issues due to construction, so I am thinking that may have been why our bathroom was closed on this day, however, I do believe that our barista could have handled this situation better.

I would love to offer you a free drink on your next visit, as we would love to keep you as one of our loyal partners and continue to serve you our coffee in a safe and calm environment as we would like our caf√© to be.

reviews.text:
Mistakes happen. Whether it be a chain coffee shop or a local one. Of course when they happen, it‚Äôs annoying. But, we‚Äôre human.
I try my best to not judge a place on the mistake, but rather, how it is corrected. Today, my first visit to Partners, I ordered a mocha latte and a spinach pretzel sandwich. They both arrived promptly. I went outside and sat down. I took a sip of coffee and unwrapped my sandwich. First thing I notice - a hair. Gross. I take a picture of it. But, it happens. I go back inside and inform a barista, showing them the hairy sandwich. They then take the sandwich and take it back to what I assume is the kitchen. Can you say health code violation? About 5 minutes later they return with a sandwich and apologize. I go back outside and study the wrapping a bit more. I unwrap the outside, compare it to the picture I previously took and realize - IT‚ÄôS THE SAME SANDWICH. Sans hair BUT warmed up. The hair was a mistake. Taking back the sandwich and not immediately throwing it away is a health code violation. Makes me wonder what other shortcuts they‚Äôre taking. Hard pass on this place.

Hey Ethan! We are extremely sorry to hear about this experience and can assure you this does not live up to our standards for customer service or health and safety measures.

We will certainly be talking with our team about this immediately to ensure our protocols are being followed. We recognize that our team did not right this mistake properly if this happened. Although we understand if not - we‚Äôd love to offer you a meal and drinks on us if you decide to come back.

If you‚Äôd like to share more details or discuss further, please reach out to hello@partnerscoffee.com!

This is by far the best coffee spot I have ever been to!
It is a nice, cozy spot right in the heart of Manhattan. It almost feels like a speakeasy; vibrant and upbeat in the front  with a quiet, peaceful space inside for some reading and getting work done. One could hang out for hours.

The best part about this coffee location is their manager, Irene and star Barista, Fitz.

reviews.responseFromOwnerText: Dear S S, We appreciate and take into consideration all of our customers feedback, and we thank you for sharing it with us. We would have preferred if you asked to speak to our manager, or owner while you were there so we can discuss face to face all your concerns. For almost a decade we have provided the best experience to all of our customers, and sometimes even we forget certain things. We apologize for not mentioning the frequent customer card. We will make sure this doesn't slip away anymore. As far as our baristas being rude we must disagree with you on this one. Our people care about every single customer, and appreciate every single person that comes to Ground Central Coffee locations. We appreciate the fact you are sharing this experience with us, as we always learn from feedback. Again thank you for visiting us 6 times. We would have wished for you to continue being a customer, but we also understand that not every place is meant for everyone. Thank you again for your feedback.

reviews.name: Julia H

reviews.responseFromOwnerText: Hi Julia H, Thank you for your feedback. We really appreciate it. Of course we encourage all our customers to come to us face to face and share these concerns. We know it's the best way to deal with any issues, or misunderstandings. As far as WiFi we have a solid connection, but sometimes we might have issues with the internet provider, which is out of our control. Our vibe is all about bringing people together to enjoy an environment that is different than the other coffee shops. It's a cozy, dark place, surrounded by books, and eclectic style of music that sometimes can be louder than other places. But, that's who we are, and what we've been cultivating successfully for almost a decade. We'd love it if you can fall in love with us as we are, but we do understand if not. Thank you again for your feedback, and for being a customer. If you ever want to speak to any of our manager, or owners please let us know.

Hi Frank,

I‚Äôm Jeff, founder / owner of PROOF Coffee Roasters.  I really appreciate your ongoing support and loyalty to our little family (and employee) owned, indie coffee company.  It means the world to me.

I am so sorry to read this review, as (you will no doubt agree) one of the most important things apart from our having an AMAZING espresso is having a consistent drink / experience.

I can tell you fairly confidently, as we have been awaiting our brand new espresso grinder on back-order (due to COVID chip shortages), that as soon as we have our new grinder, any anomaly inconsistencies will be completely ironed out.  Our training across the board with regard to espresso extraction methods, steaming, pouring, etc. are very rigorous specifically *because* we mandate a consistent experience with consistent beverages, and I sincerely apologize for the (very temporary) inconvenience we are all up against right now.

Given the above explanation of the circumstances, I hope that perhaps this can help reshape your initial perception / perspective, knowing that we very much care about quality and consistency, and that your experience is assuredly not due to any lack of care or training; it‚Äôs purely a COVID pain point in awaiting our grinder.

I‚Äôd be honored, after hopefully  understanding this clarification and explanation (and our shared challenges during COVID, which we are all ‚Äústuck in‚Äù together), if you might accept my humble request to give a moment of consideration to perhaps updating your review based on what is hopefully a different perspective based on the above information ‚Äî as a very small business, especially coming out the other side of COVID, every single review makes such a marked impact to us, both positively and negatively, and it seems clear you‚Äôve been coming to PROOF for quite a while and therefore probably know full well how much love and passion and care we imbue into everything we do, and our gratitude for people like you who keep us in business with your kind support and loyalty.

reviews.responseFromOwnerText:
Hi Kristian,

I'm Jeff, founder of PROOF Coffee Roasters -- thank you for your kind words on loving our coffee, and I appreciate your stopping in and making us a part of your day.

I wanted to respond directly to two considerations you raised in your post, because I can understand how perspective is everything and I wanted to hopefully put things in a better perspective for you as well as for anyone else who may read this review.

1). Coffee price: We are 100% Certified Organic, single origin coffee (not a blend, where one can sometimes masque sub-par beans in with other decent beans in order to save cost), and we give 5% proceeds across the board to 2 mental health charities.  Additionally, incidentally, despite all of the above, we have not raised our prices (yet) in the 6 years we have been in business, and at this point are not only drastically underpriced for the value of the product we offer, but we are underpriced compared to even Starbucks coffees of the same size, let alone other specialty coffee cafes in NYC.  People tend to space out prices at Starbucks, and only realize what they are paying when they go to a place with even better product (not that I'm biased or anything ;) but have the price of the drink given to them front and center instead of hidden on a small green dot matrix display.

2). 10 cups of coffee = reward.  Again, perspective being everything, I'll harken back to something my mother used to tell me, tongue in cheek: "No good deed ever goes un-punished".  Not only do we have a rewards program, but we also did away with paper punch cards like many places use in order to help save trees and keep our environment clean and do our part in the world -- it would be less expensive for us to use punch cards, incidentally, as the Square rewards program is quite expensive to utilize.  Further, we could simply have no rewards program at all, which is the case at many specialty coffee spots, but we choose to provide this (at a sizable expense to us) as a small token of our appreciation to our loyal folks who come in often.  $2 off a cup is better than nothing at all, and to be candid, I'm a little surprised at being laughed at online for trying to offer a small "thank you" as a reward to regulars.

I'm not sure if maybe you were having a bad day or something when you posted this review, and if so, believe me I totally get how that goes. Especially in the city, stress is high, we are always in a hurry, things go wrong often / are inconvenient often, and our smile wears thin.  It happens to the best of us, and I'm sure you are probably a very thoughtful, kind person given the fact that you are a local guide, are so active on Google, post so many photos, etc. -- you obviously seem to care about your community.  I would ask you, from the heart, that even if you don't consider perhaps modifying this review to better reflect an updated perspective now, that at least maybe you might consider in the future reaching out to an establishment first before sort of making fun of a family business doing what they can (however small) to thank loyal customers for being a part of their lives.

Yours sincerely,
Jeff

reviews.name: Morris Harrar
reviews.text:
Why do people go to coffee shops? For Coffee, yes, but mostly for the experience.  Stump town coffee is by far the most humiliating experience in coffee shops ever.
They treat customers as if we were giving out products for free.  Their coffee is not even that outstanding.  It is ok, their croissants from Pain davignon, they are good, not outstanding either, the pain au chocolat barely has any chocolate.   They charged me at 8 am 9 dollars and change for a cappuccino and a pain au chocolate   1 hour later they charged me for the same size cappuccino and same pain au chocolate almost 12 dollars.  I complained.  They could care less.  And on top of it with an attitude.  They are definitely on my not to go back list    Horrible feeling
